The Familiar Aspect of the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism long before these threats become generally visible?
Because they know that apparently "harmless" remarks can escalate into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination that then becomes legally enshrined.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake.
Thus, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the presidential elections in France, it has become clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other crude right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often mere followers of fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - with the "educated bourgeoisie" in connection with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in language that often resembles that of the hangers-on of these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, fortunately - but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to Britain should be mentioned: recently, he referred to Israel during a dinner party in London as "this damned little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
What is alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
He was neither recalled by his government, nor did the Blair government demand his recall. In public, the matter was treated as just another scandal to be swept aside.
The French press seriously portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British petty manners, rather than of his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador in Britain has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard nevertheless did us a service: through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish sentiments are.
As a columnist put it so accurately: Israel has become the object of hatred, whose name one dares not utter.
We must not only dare to say it, we are even obligated to speak it out.
Given the daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Antisemitic incidents are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, Holland, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that Holocaust denial has become commonplace. Nor must we remain silent about the comparisons that antisemites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television show Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. People hate them almost everywhere."
During a televised Friday prayer broadcast on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Jewish hatred is not checked, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as much as non-Jews.
Currently, the targets of this fight are blurrier than ever before, because an astonishing aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism has always been the same - namely, to attack Jews - it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this did not succeed, Jews were expelled or killed.
When in the 19th century racial theory captured people's imagination, Jews were attacked for belonging to a wicked race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today slandered as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is entirely legitimate to critically oppose certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Antizionism, however, is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Antizionists sometimes claim that they are not against Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of the United Kingdom, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, yet hate their state.
And yet, in connection with Israel, there are people who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, Israel-bashing is on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state system in the Near East is a core aspect of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all good and the source of all evil," then within the UN, the "doctrine of contempt" is circulating, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of Canada's parliament, expresses it.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
So liegen den zahlreichen anti-jüdischen Übergriffen in vielen Ländern die Verteufelungen Israels zugrunde, die sich einer antisemitischen Terminologie bedienen.
Attacken auf Synagogen werden oftmals durch die Verwendung dieser verleumderischen Sprache im Zusammenhang mit dem Nahen Osten ausgelöst.
Im Vergleich zu früheren anti-jüdischen Ausbrüchen, handelt es sich bei dem heutigen Antisemitismus weniger um Angriffe auf einzelne Juden, als vielmehr um eine Attacke gegen den "kollektiven Juden", also gegen den Staat Israel.
Derartige Attacken haben aber eine Kettenreaktion von Übergriffen auf einzelne Juden und jüdische Institutionen in ganz Europa und Lateinamerika in Gang gesetzt.
Früher waren die gefährlichsten Antisemiten diejenigen, die die Welt judenrein machen wollten.
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world free of Jewish states.
